rules: Rule1: If the project has zoning approval, then the project completed the foundation phase.
Rule2: Provided that the project has zoning approval, the project has building permit approval.
Rule3: Either the project has zoning approval or the project has environmental approval.
Rule4: If the project has delay coverage insurance, then the insurance policy has active coverage.
Rule5: Assuming the insurance policy has active coverage, if failing to complete the foundation phase implies not being on schedule, then the project incurred a cost overrun.
Rule6: Provided that steel material is available at the site, the crew can proceed with foundation work.
Rule7: If steel material is available at the site, then the engineer approved an alternative composite material.
Rule8: In the event that the engineer approved an alternative composite material, the crew cannot proceed with foundation work.
Rule9: If the project has environmental approval, then the project is on schedule.
Rule10: Provided the contractor submitted a zoning application, if the project has building permit approval, then the project is on schedule.
Rule11: Either the contractor submitted a zoning application or the contractor submitted an environmental application.
Rule12: Assuming the contractor submitted an environmental application, if the project has building permit approval, then the project is on schedule.
Rule13: If the project has complete funding, then the project is on schedule.
Rule14: In the event that the project has a steel material delay, steel material is available at the site.
Rule15: Provided that the contractor received a deadline extension, if there is a steel material delay for the project, then the project has a schedule delay.
Rule16: Either the contractor received a deadline extension or the contractor received a penalty.
Rule17: If it is not the case that receiving a penalty implies that a steel material delay leads to a schedule delay, then the owner terminated the contractor's contract.
Rule18: In the event that the project does not have complete funding, the project has a steel material delay.
facts: Fact1: The project has delay coverage insurance.
Fact2: It is not the case that the owner terminated the contractor's contract.
Fact3: It is not the case that the project incurred a cost overrun.
Fact4: The project does not have a schedule delay.
